# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: media-capabilities
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The **`decodingInfo()`** method of the `MediaCapabilities` interface returns a promise that fulfils with information about how well the user agent can decode/display media with a given configuration.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The resolved object contains three boolean properties `supported`, `smooth`, and `powerefficient`, which indicate whether decoding the media described would be supported, and if so, whether decoding would be smooth and power-efficient.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The method can also be used to test the user agent capabilities for decoding media encoded with a key system, but only when called in the main thread and in a secure context.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] If the configuration passed in the `configuration.keySystemConfiguration` property is supported for decoding the data, the resolved promise also includes a `MediaKeySystemAccess` object that can be used to create a `MediaKeys` object to setup encrypted playback.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] Represents a configuration that is meant to be used for a plain file playback.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] Represents a configuration that is meant to be used for playback of a `MediaSource`.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] Represents a configuration that is meant to be received using `RTCPeerConnection` (not allowed when `keySystemConfiguration` is set).
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] Configuration object for a video media source.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] String containing a valid video MIME type, and (optionally) a `codecs` parameter.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The number of bits used to encode one second of the video file.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The number of frames making up one second of video playback.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] Configuration object for an audio media source.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] String containing a valid audio MIME type, and (optionally) a `codecs` parameter.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The number of channels used by the audio track.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The number of bits used to encode one second of the audio file.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The number of audio samples making up one second of the audio file.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] Object specifying the key system configuration for encrypted media.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] If specified, the `type` must be `media-source` or `file` (not `webrtc`).
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] A string identifying the media key system.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] For example `org.w3.clearkey` or `com.widevine.alpha`.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] A string indicating the data type name the initialization data format, such as `"cenc"`, `"keyids"` and `"webm"`.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] Allowed names are defined in the Encrypted Media Extensions Initialization Data Format Registry.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] A string indicating whether the implementation may use "distinctive identifiers" (or distinctive permanent identifiers) for any operations associated with any object created from this configuration.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The returned object must support this feature.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The returned object may support this feature.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The returned object must not support or use this feature.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] A string indicating whether the returned object must be able to persist session data or any other type of state.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] Only "temporary" sessions may be created when persistent state is not allowed.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] An array of strings indicating the session types that must be supported.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] A session for which the license, key(s) and record of or data related to the session are not persisted.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The application does not need to manage such storage.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] Implementations must support this option, and it is the default.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] A session for which the license (and potentially other data related to the session) will be persisted.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] A record of the license and associated keys persists even if the license is destroyed, providing an attestation that the license and key(s) it contains are no longer usable by the client.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The audio key system track configuration associated with the `audio` configuration above.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] If set, then the `audio` configuration must also be set.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The encryption scheme associated with the content type, such as `cenc`, `cbcs`, `cbcs-1-9`.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] This value should be set by an application (it defaults to `null`, indicating that any encryption scheme may be used).
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The robustness level associated with the content type.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The empty string indicates that any ability to decrypt and decode the content type is acceptable.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The video key system track configuration associated with the `video` configuration above.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] If set, then the `video` configuration must also be set.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] `true` if the media content can be decoded at all.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] `true` if playback of the media can be played at the frame rate specified by the configuration without needing to drop frames.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] `true` if playback of the media will be power efficient.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] A `MediaKeySystemAccess` that can be used to create a `MediaKeys` object to setup encrypted playback, or `null` if decoding is not supported using the supplied configuration.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] Browsers will report a supported media configuration as `smooth` and `powerEfficient` until stats on this device have been recorded.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] All supported audio codecs report `powerEfficient` as true.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The method is called in a worker when `configuration.keySystemConfiguration` is defined.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The method is called outside of a secure context and `configuration.keySystemConfiguration` is defined.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] `decodingInfo()` and the `Navigator.requestMediaKeySystemAccess()` method of the Encrypted Media Extensions API reflect fundamentally different approaches for selecting a configuration for decoding encrypted media.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The configuration parameter for `Navigator.requestMediaKeySystemAccess()` takes an array of possible configurations and allows the system to choose the one that it considers appropriate.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] By contrast, `decodingInfo()` takes one configuration at a time.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The expectation is that the caller will execute `decodingInfo()` multiple times, starting with the most preferred configurations and stopping as soon as it finds a configuration that meets application requirements for being smooth, power-efficient, or both.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] In other words, the selection decision is devolved to the caller.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] This example shows how to create a media configuration for an audio file and then use it in `MediaCapabilities.decodingInfo()`.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] Similarly, the code below shows the configuration for a video file.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] This example shows how you might use `decodingInfo()` to select a media configuration for encrypted content.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] As in the previous example we define a media configuration, but this time we use the `type` of `media-source` (rather than `file`), and specify both audio and video content.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] We also specify a simple `keySystemConfiguration`.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] In the previous example we used promise chaining, to wait on the result.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] Here we've chosen to use `async` and `await` to wait on the result, and then log it.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] The previous example showed how you can use `decodingInfo()` to get information for just one configuration.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] In reality the method would normally be called iteratively with a number of configurations, selecting the first supported configuration that matches the application's criteria for smooth playing or power efficiency.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] Assuming we already have an `Array` of media configurations named `orderedMediaConfigs`, which we have ordered from most to least wanted, we can use the `Array.prototype.map()` to call `decodingInfo()` for each configuration and get an array containing all the returned `Promise` objects.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] We then use a `for await...of` loop to iterate the promises as they resolve.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] In the loop we store the last supported configuration to `nonSmoothConfig`, and we exit the loop as soon as we find a smooth configuration, setting this as our `bestConfig`.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] If we found a smooth and supported configuration while looping (`bestConfig`) we use it to create our media keys and decode the media.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] If we didn't discover any smooth configurations we might instead use `nonSmoothConfig` to decode the media.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] This will be the supported configuration that was found last, which because of the way we ordered the original `orderedMediaConfigs`, should be the one with the lowest framerate.
[src:media-capabilities/decodinginfo] If there are no supported configuration, we have no choice but to fail and notify the user.
[src:media-capabilities/media-capabilities-api] The **Media Capabilities API** allows developers to determine decoding and encoding abilities of the device, exposing information such as whether media is supported and whether playback should be smooth and power efficient.
[src:media-capabilities/media-capabilities-api] There are a myriad of video and audio codecs.
[src:media-capabilities/media-capabilities-api] Different browsers support different media types and new media types are always being developed.
[src:media-capabilities/media-capabilities-api] With the Media Capabilities API, developers can ensure each user is getting the best bitrate and storage savings for their browser, device, and OS capabilities.
[src:media-capabilities/media-capabilities-api] Whether a device uses hardware or software decoding impacts how smooth and power efficient the video decoding is and how efficient the playback will be.
[src:media-capabilities/media-capabilities-api] The Media Capabilities API enables developers to determine which codecs are supported and how performant a media file will be both in terms of smoothness and power efficiency.
[src:media-capabilities/media-capabilities-api] The Media Capabilities API provide more powerful features than other APIs such as `MediaRecorder.isTypeSupported()` or `HTMLMediaElement.canPlayType()`, which only address general browser support, not performance.
[src:media-capabilities/media-capabilities-api] To test support, smoothness, and power efficiency for encoding and decoding video or audio content, you use the `MediaCapabilities` interface's `encodingInfo()` and `decodingInfo()` methods.
[src:media-capabilities/media-capabilities-api] Provides information about the decoding abilities of the device, system and browser based on codecs, profile, resolution, and bitrates.
[src:media-capabilities/media-capabilities-api] The information can be used to serve optimal media streams to the user and determine if playback should be smooth and power efficient.
[src:media-capabilities/media-capabilities-api] A `MediaCapabilities` object that can expose information about the decoding and encoding capabilities for a given media format and output capabilities.
[src:media-capabilities/media-capabilities-api] This example defines an audio configuration then checks to see if the user agent supports decoding that media configuration, and whether it will perform well in terms of smoothness and power efficiency.
[src:media-capabilities/mediacapabilities] The **`MediaCapabilities`** interface of the Media Capabilities API provides information about the decoding abilities of the device, system and browser.
[src:media-capabilities/mediacapabilities] The API can be used to query the browser about the decoding abilities of the device based on codecs, profile, resolution, and bitrates.
[src:media-capabilities/mediacapabilities] The information is accessed through the **`mediaCapabilities`** property of the `Navigator` and `WorkerNavigator` interface.
[src:media-capabilities/mediacapabilities] When passed a valid media configuration, it returns a promise with information as to whether the media type is supported, and whether encoding such media would be smooth and power efficient.
[src:media-capabilities/mediacapabilities] When passed a valid media configuration, it returns a promise with information as to whether the media type is supported, and whether decoding such media would be smooth and power efficient.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] In the analog video world, transcoding can be performed just while files are being searched, as well as for presentation.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] For example, Cineon and DPX files have been widely used as a common format for digital cinema, but the data size of a two-hour movie is about 8 terabytes (TB).
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] That large size can increase the cost and difficulty of handling movie files.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] However, transcoding into a JPEG2000 lossless format has better data compression performance than other lossless coding technologies; in many cases, JPEG2000 can compress images to half their original size.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] Transcoding is commonly a lossy process, introducing generation loss; however, transcoding can be lossless if the output is either losslessly compressed or uncompressed.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] Transcoding is a two-step process in which the original data is decoded to an intermediate uncompressed format (e.g., PCM for audio; YUV for video), which is then encoded into the target format.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] image), one will generally decode it, edit it, then re-encode it.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] , and make all edits on that copy, rather than repeatedly re-encoding it.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] Similarly, if encoding to a lossy format is required, it should be deferred until the data is finalised, e.g., after mastering.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] , but may use an identical sampling rate with higher compression.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] , and is used if the output resolution differs from the resolution of the media.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] One can also use formats with bitrate peeling, which allow one to easily lower the bitrate without re-encoding, but quality is often lower than a re-encode.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] For example, in Vorbis, bitrate peeling as of 2008, the quality is inferior to re-encoding.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] The key drawback of transcoding in lossy formats is decreased quality.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] Compression artifacts are cumulative, so transcoding causes a progressive loss of quality with each successive generation, known as digital generation loss.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] For this reason, transcoding (in lossy formats) is generally discouraged unless unavoidable.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] These lossless formats can be transcoded to PCM formats or transcoded directly from one lossless format to another lossless format, without any loss in quality.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] They can be transcoded into a lossy format, but these copies will then not be able to be transcoded into another format of any kind (PCM, lossless, or lossy) without a subsequent loss of quality.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] For image editing users are advised to capture or save images in a raw or uncompressed format, and then edit a copy of that master version, only converting to lossy formats if smaller file sized images are needed for final distribution.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] As with audio, transcoding from lossy format to another format of any type will result in a loss of quality.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] For video editing, (for video converting), images are normally compressed directly during the recording process due to the huge file sizes that would be created if they were not, and because the huge storage demands being too cumbersome for the user otherwise.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] Although transcoding can be found in many areas of content adaptation, it is commonly used in the area of mobile phone content adaptation.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] In this case, transcoding is a must, due to the diversity of mobile devices and their capabilities.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] This diversity requires an intermediate state of content adaptation in order to make sure that the source content will adequately function on the target device to which it is sent.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] Transcoding video from most consumer digital cameras can reduce the file size significantly while keeping the quality about the same.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] This is possible because most consumer cameras are real-time, power-constrained devices having neither the processing power nor the robust power supplies of desktop CPUs.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] One of the most popular technologies in which transcoding is used is the Multimedia Messaging Service (MMS), which is the technology used to send or receive messages with media (image, sound, text and video) between mobile phones.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] For example, when a camera phone is used to take a digital picture, a high-quality image of at least 640 × 480 pixels is created.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] When sending the image to another phone, this high-resolution image might be transcoded to a lower-resolution image with fewer colors in order to better fit the target device's screen size and color limitations.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] This size and color reduction improves the user experience on the target device, and is sometimes the only way for content to be sent between different mobile devices.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] Transcoding is extensively used by home theatre PC software to reduce the usage of disk space by video files.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] The most common operation in this application is the transcoding of MPEG-2 files to the MPEG-4 or H.264 format.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] Real-time transcoding in a many-to-many way (any input format to any output format) is becoming a necessity to provide true search capability for any multimedia content on any mobile device, with over 500 million videos on the web and a plethora of mobile devices.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] Before the advent of semiconductors and integrated circuits, real-time resolution and frame rate transcoding between different analog video standards was achieved by a CRT/camera tube combination.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] The CRT part does not write onto a phosphor, but onto a thin, dielectric target; the camera part reads the deposited charge pattern at a different scan rate from the back side of this target.
[src:media-capabilities/transcoding] The setup could also be used as a genlock.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] A **video codec** is software or hardware that compresses and decompresses digital video.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] In the context of video compression, *codec* is a portmanteau of *encoder* and *decoder*, while a device that only compresses is typically called an *encoder*, and one that only decompresses is a *decoder*.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] The compressed data format usually conforms to a standard video coding format.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] The compression is typically lossy, meaning that the compressed video lacks some information present in the original video.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] A consequence of this is that decompressed video has lower quality than the original, uncompressed video because there is insufficient information to accurately reconstruct the original video.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] There are complex relationships between the video quality, the amount of data used to represent the video (determined by the bit rate), the complexity of the encoding and decoding algorithms, sensitivity to data losses and errors, ease of editing, random access, and end-to-end delay (latency).
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Historically, video was stored as an analog signal on magnetic tape.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Around the time when the compact disc entered the market as a digital-format replacement for analog audio, it became feasible to also store and convey video in digital form.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Because of the large amount of storage and bandwidth needed to record and convey raw video, a method was needed to reduce the amount of data used to represent the raw video.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Since then, engineers and mathematicians have developed a number of solutions for achieving this goal that involve compressing the digital video data.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] In 1974, discrete cosine transform (DCT) compression was introduced by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] During the late 1980s, a number of companies began experimenting with DCT lossy compression for video coding, leading to the development of the H.261 standard.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] H.261 was the first practical video coding standard, and was developed by a number of companies, including Hitachi, PictureTel, NTT, BT, and Toshiba, among others.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Since H.261, DCT compression has been adopted by all the major video coding standards that followed.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] The most popular video coding standards used for codecs have been the MPEG standards.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] MPEG-1 was developed by the Motion Picture Experts Group (MPEG) in 1991, and it was designed to compress VHS-quality video.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] It was succeeded in 1994 by MPEG-2/H.262, which was developed by a number of companies, primarily Sony, Thomson and Mitsubishi Electric.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] MPEG-2 became the standard video format for DVD and SD digital television.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] In 1999, it was followed by MPEG-4/H.263, which was a major leap forward for video compression technology.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] It was developed by a number of companies, primarily Mitsubishi Electric, Hitachi and Panasonic.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] The most widely used video coding format, as of 2016, is H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] It was developed in 2003 by a number of organizations, primarily Panasonic, Godo Kaisha IP Bridge and LG Electronics.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] H.264 is the main video encoding standard for Blu-ray Discs, and is widely used by streaming internet services such as YouTube, Netflix, Vimeo, and iTunes Store, web software such as Adobe Flash Player and Microsoft Silverlight, and various HDTV broadcasts over terrestrial and satellite television.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] AVC has been succeeded by HEVC (H.265), developed in 2013.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] It is heavily patented, with the majority of patents belonging to Samsung Electronics, GE, NTT and JVC Kenwood.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] The adoption of HEVC has been hampered by its complex licensing structure.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] HEVC is, in turn, succeeded by Versatile Video Coding (VVC).
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] There are also the open and free VP8, VP9 and AV1 video coding formats, used by YouTube, all of which were developed with involvement from Google.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Video codecs are used in DVD players, Internet video, video on demand, digital cable, digital terrestrial television, videotelephony and a variety of other applications.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] In particular, they are widely used in applications that record or transmit video, which may not be feasible with the high data volumes and bandwidths of uncompressed video.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] For example, they are used in operating theaters to record surgical operations, in IP cameras in security systems, and in remotely operated underwater vehicles and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Any video stream or file can be encoded using a wide variety of live video format options.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Video codecs seek to represent a fundamentally analog data set in a digital format.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Because of the design of analog video signals, which represent luminance (luma) and color information (chrominance, chroma) separately, a common first step in image compression in codec design is to represent and store the image in a YCbCr color space.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] It is common to represent the ratios of information stored in these different channels in the following way YCbCr.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Different codecs use different chroma subsampling ratios as appropriate to their compression needs.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Video compression schemes for Web and DVD make use of a 4:2:1 color sampling pattern, and the DV standard uses 4:1:1 sampling ratios.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Professional video codecs designed to function at much higher bitrates and to record a greater amount of color information for post-production manipulation, sample in 4:2:2 and 4:4:4 ratios.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Examples of these codecs include Panasonic's DVCPRO50 and DVCPROHD codecs (4:2:2), Sony's HDCAM-SR (4:4:4), Panasonic's HDD5 (4:2:2), Apple's Prores HQ 422 (4:2:2).
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] It is also worth noting that video codecs can operate in RGB space as well.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] These codecs tend not to sample the red, green, and blue channels in different ratios, since there is less perceptual motivation for doing so—just the blue channel could be undersampled.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Some amount of spatial and temporal downsampling may also be used to reduce the raw data rate before the basic encoding process.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] The most popular encoding transform is the 8x8 DCT.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Codecs that make use of a wavelet transform are also entering the market, especially in camera workflows that involve dealing with RAW image formatting in motion sequences.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] This process involves representing the video image as a set of macroblocks.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] For more information about this critical facet of video codec design, see B-frames.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] The output of the transform is first quantized, then entropy encoding is applied to the quantized values.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] The entropy coding method typically uses variable-length coding tables.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Some encoders compress the video in a multiple-step process called *n-pass* encoding (e.g.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] 2-pass), which performs a slower but potentially higher quality compression.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] The decoding process consists of performing, to the extent possible, an inversion of each stage of the encoding process.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] The one stage that cannot be exactly inverted is the quantization stage.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] There, a best-effort approximation of inversion is performed.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] This part of the process is often called *inverse quantization* or *dequantization*, although quantization is an inherently non-invertible process.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Video codec designs are usually standardized or eventually become standardized—i.e., specified precisely in a published document.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] However, only the decoding process need be standardized to enable interoperability.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] The encoding process is typically not specified at all in a standard, and implementers are free to design their encoder however they want, as long as the video can be decoded in the specified manner.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] For this reason, the quality of the video produced by decoding the results of different encoders that use the same video codec standard can vary dramatically from one encoder implementation to another.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] A variety of video compression formats can be implemented on PCs and in consumer electronics equipment.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] It is therefore possible for multiple codecs to be available in the same product, reducing the need to choose a single dominant video compression format to achieve interoperability.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Standard video compression formats can be supported by multiple encoder and decoder implementations from multiple sources.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] For example, video encoded with a standard MPEG-4 Part 2 codec such as Xvid can be decoded using any other standard MPEG-4 Part 2 codec such as FFmpeg MPEG-4 or DivX Pro Codec, because they all use the same video format.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Codecs have their qualities and drawbacks.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] The trade-off between compression power, speed, and fidelity (including artifacts) is usually considered the most important figure of technical merit.
[src:media-capabilities/video-codec] Online video material is encoded by a variety of codecs, and this has led to the availability of codec packs — a pre-assembled set of commonly used codecs combined with an installer available as a software package for PCs, such as K-Lite Codec Pack, Perian and Combined Community Codec Pack.
